title: For Sale:  AMT Lightning .22 Match Pistol, Stainless
postcontent:
Hard to find AMT (Arcadia Machine And Tool) Lightning Match pistol, caliber .22 Long Rifle, Semi Automatic, 6-in bull barreled, all Stainless steel match Pistol. This AMT Stainless Match Pistol is almost an exact replica of the Ruger MK Original .22LR Pistol. The big difference is the AMT is all Stainless. So close were the designs that AMT was taken to court by Ruger for Patent Infringement. That court case terminated the AMT Production line.

AMT production ran from 1986 through 1993. Their production facility was located in Covina, California. The AMT Lightning match pistol is said to be one of the most accurate and reliable pistols of its kind. This 6-inch bull barrel has a fixed blade front sight and an adjustable Millet rear sight. This pistol has black rubber grips, a custom target trigger, is in excellent condition and has a low round count. It also comes with four-10 round magazines.

If you have always wanted a special .22 target pistol, this one is waiting for you. Price is $600.00 or best offer (National gun auction prices start at $700.00 for this type pistol)

title: For Sale:  Nickel Whitney Wolverine only 500 made! With original Box! RARE!
postcontent:
Original Nickel Whitney Wolverine 22lr pistol with original box and nomenclature. Only 500 made in the 1950's. One in similar condition just sold for $3,162 at the Rock Island Auction. This is an extremely rare piece of history as it is the first pistol produced with an aluminum frame. The pistol is mechanically sound and functions perfect. The nickel plating is a little dull in some spots due to being kept in a leather holster. The box has a little bit of staining on it, but it still has the sticker on the bottom, which I am told is rare!

The Whitney Wolverine was an advanced, "space-aged", light-weight aluminum, semi-automatic, .22 LR caliber pistol created in 1956. It had a 10 round magazine, a barrel 4.625 inches (117.5 mm) long and a weight of only 23 ounces (650 g)

The Wolverine was engineered by Robert Hillberg, who learned about aluminum casting during WWII while working with aircraft guns and later became research engineer for High Standard Manufacturing Company.[3] Only 13,371 of these .22 semi automatic pistols were made in its short period of production between 1956 and 1958.[4] There were approximately 500 nickel plated according to company records, the rest finished in varying shades of anodized blue, The plastic grips came in either a black,dark brown or white, the white grips are found mostly on the nickel plated models. The frame being investment cast by Alcoa was a new idea for the gun industry at the time, now it is widely used by almost every major gun manufacturer today.

More Pics can be provided if needed.
$2,750

title: For Sale:  Cast lead bullets - 9mm, 38 special, 357 mag
postcontent:
Lee 158-RF  wide flat nose bullet cast of either 10 BHN alloy or 18 BHN alloy. Sized to .359. https://www.grafs.com/uploads/pictures/128/lee90303.jpg

Also available is the Lee 125-RF flat nose. This bullet is for 38 or 357, but can also be sized down to .3565 for use in 9mm. This is also available in either alloy. http://www.titanreloading.com/image/cache/data/Products/90306-600x600.jpg

10 BHN alloy begins to mushroom at impact velocities of 1300 fps. You may prefer the harder alloy for better penetration.  It is needed in faster twist rifles like Marlin and Handi Rifles to maintain accuracy in the 1600-1800 fps range. It is also needed in 1 in 10" fast twist 9mms. 

 The only time we run harder bullets for pistols is in 9mm. This is because the common 1 in 10" twist rate is too much for the softer bullets. 357 mag has a gentler twist rate of 1 in 16" and the medium alloy works great there all the way to max loads. In the slow twist ( 1 in 30") of our Rossi rifles, 10 BHN shoots 2 MOA at 1800 FPS with Lil' Gun and expands to 55-60 cal in water all the way to 150 yards. 



Prices: 

25$/500 125-RF 10 BHN 
30$/500 125-RF 18 BHN
30$/500 158-RF 10 BHN
35$/500 158-RF 18 BHN

All bullets are tumble lubed.

title: For Sale:  Echo ASR-1 Bolt-Action Spring Rifle (30 OBO)
postcontent:
This listing is for this rifle in question: http://www.airsoftgi.com/product_info.php?products_id=6572

This rifle was purchased some time ago by a friend who wanted to introduce me to Airsoft. While under enemy fire, we threw ourselves into a ditch for cover. Having not yet grown into full coordination of my limbs, I fell on the rifle, breaking the stock from the receiver. Disheartened, we did a thorough but messy JB Weld job to put it back together. It remains, to this day, functional, but has never seen action since. 

Now several years later, I have rediscovered it, although my Airsoft days are long behind me. As it is taking up space, I feel the best thing to do is get rid of it, although I don't want to throw it away - and I did spend money on it.  I've heavily discounted it for the damage, which is listed below:

- Stock broke off from the receiver and has been JB Welded back together. (This is the main issue). The fix appears solid and it can be cocked without issue.
- Due to the impromptu nature of the repair job, there are JB Weld smears around the stock and grip and part of the receiver.
- The tripod in the picture does not seem to want to stay on, but has never wanted to stay on in the first place.
- Pictures have been included that hopefully show the apperance.

This would make a good first airsoft rifle for someone young perhaps, or just getting into the game. As I am not familiar with the rules for selling airsoft weapons, I will treat it like an actual rifle - AZ ID required, over 18 only, and will ask if you are prohibited from possessing a weapon. If you have any questions or would like to inspect, please do not hesitate to contact me.

title: For Sale:  Cast lead bullets - 9mm, 357 and 38 special
postcontent:
Lee 158-RF wide flat nose bullet cast of either 10 BHN alloy or 18 BHN alloy. Sized to .359. https://www.grafs.com/uploads/pictures/128/lee90303.jpg

Also available is the Lee 125-RF flat nose. This bullet is for 38 or 357, but can also be sized down to .3565 for use in 9mm. This is also available in either alloy. http://www.titanreloading.com/image/cache/data/Products/90306-600x600.jpg

You may prefer the harder alloy for better penetration. It is needed in faster twist rifles like Marlin and Handi Rifles to maintain accuracy in the 1600-1800 fps range. It is also needed in 1 in 10" fast twist 9mms. 

The only time we run harder bullets for pistols is in 9mm. This is because the common 1 in 10" twist rate is too much for the softer bullets. 357 mag has a gentler twist rate of 1 in 16" and the medium alloy works great there all the way to max loads. 10 BHN begins to mushroom at impact velocities of 1300 fps. In the slow twist ( 1 in 30") of our Rossi rifles, 10 BHN shoots 2 MOA at 1800 FPS with Lil' Gun and expands to 55-60 cal in water all the way to 150 yards. 



Prices: 

25$/500 125-RF 10 BHN 
30$/500 125-RF 18 BHN
30$/500 158-RF 10 BHN
35$/500 158-RF 18 BHN

All bullets are tumble lubed.

title: For Sale:  Mossberg Model 152
postcontent:
The Mossberg Model 152 was manufactured from about 1948-1952. The Model 152 was a semiautomatic .22 caliber carbine with an 18" barrel that used a rear peep sight & military-type front sight and had a 7-shot detachable box magazine. The stock was Monte Carlo styled with a pistol grip and included a forearm that hinged down to act like a hand grip. The sling was mounted on swivels on the left side of the stock.
I last shot this 50 years ago when I was 10 years old.
